<h1>@HI{{ga}} conjunction</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> @S1{{}} <strong>@HI{{ga}}</strong> @S2{{}}
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
@HI{{ga}} can operate as a conjunction that lightly links two sentences of contrasting meaning.
</p>

<h2> Examples </h2>

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{before^salute}}<strong>ga</strong>, o@KJ{{evening^in*front}}ha?}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Excuse me, but may I have your name?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</ol>

<h2> Notes </h2>

<p>
@S1{{}} and @S2{{}} may be either formal or casual, but they must both be the same form.
</p>

<p>
In some utterances @S1{{}} and @S2{{}} do not need to express contrasting notions.
</p>

<p>
@S2{{}} can be omitted if the meaning is obvious.
</p>

<p>
@S1{{}} and @S2{{}} are independent clauses and each can stand on their own. Contrast this with
@HI{{keredomo}}, where @S1{{}} would be a subordinate clause.
</p>

